{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637892"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:46:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:46:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17678"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17678","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17678"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.18,0,0,0.07,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10392"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75880"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10392","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10392"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17678"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61393"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10514"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24280"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24297"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75880","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75880"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with acute blood loss following trauma. Her blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg and heart rate is 110 beats per minute.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer doctors note activation of compensatory mechanisms to maintain blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary stimulus for renin secretion from the kidney?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased plasma sodium concentration","Increased blood volume","Decreased plasma potassium concentration","Increased sympathetic stimulation of alpha receptors","Decreased renal perfusion pressure"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary stimulus for renin secretion is \u003Cstrong\u003Edecreased renal perfusion pressure\u003C/strong\u003E, which is detected by baroreceptors in the afferent arteriole. This triggers juxtaglomerular cells to release renin, initiating the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased plasma sodium concentration\u003C/strong\u003E - High plasma sodium levels suppress renin release through negative feedback mechanisms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased blood volume\u003C/strong\u003E - Elevated blood volume increases renal perfusion pressure which inhibits renin release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased plasma potassium concentration\u003C/strong\u003E - Changes in potassium primarily influence aldosterone secretion rather than directly affecting renin release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased sympathetic stimulation of alpha receptors\u003C/strong\u003E - Alpha-adrenergic stimulation causes vasoconstriction but does not directly trigger renin release.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther stimuli for renin release include beta-adrenergic stimulation and decreased sodium delivery to the macula densa cells. The released renin then converts angiotensinogen to angiotensin I, which is subsequently converted to the active angiotensin II by angiotensin converting enzyme.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Renin is secreted by juxtaglomerular cells in response to decreased renal perfusion pressure.","Renin converts angiotensinogen to angiotensin I as the first step in the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system.","Beta-adrenergic stimulation, decreased sodium delivery to distal tubules, and decreased renal perfusion pressure all stimulate renin release."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61393"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17678"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61393"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-01T07:57:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T12:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10392"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75880"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","posi